novos-modelos.title: Z.ai GLM 4.6: What We Learned From 100 Million Open Source Downloads ‚Äî Yuxuan Zhang, Z.ai
novos-modelos.description:
GLM 4.6 is the only open-source model currently tied for #1 on the LMSYS Chatbot Arena, standing shoulder-to-shoulder with GPT-4o and Claude 3.5 Sonnet. In this talk, Zhang Yuxuan from zAI breaks down the technical roadmap that led to over 100 million downloads across the GLM family.

Zhang deep dives into the specific training recipes behind GLM 4.6, including their move to single-stage Reinforcement Learning (RL), the "SLIME" RL framework for handling complex agent trajectories, and how they structured 15 trillion tokens of pre-training data. If you are building AI Agents or training LLMs, this breakdown offers a rare look inside the architecture of a frontier-class open-source model.

In this video, we cover:

The Data Recipe: How zAI filters 15T tokens, moves to repo-level code contexts, and integrates agentic reasoning data.

SLIME Framework: A look at the hybrid synchronous/asynchronous architecture used to train agents without bottlenecking GPU clusters.

RL Lessons: Why zAI abandoned multi-stage RL in favor of single-stage training to preserve long-context capabilities.

GLM 4.5V: How native resolution processing improves UI navigation and video understanding.

Timestamps:
0:00 - Introduction & The GLM Ecosystem
0:55 - 100 Million Downloads & Open Source Roadmap
03:22 - Tying GPT-4o on LMSYS Arena
05:04 - The Training Pipeline: From Pre-training to Long Context
07:54 - Introducing SLIME: Efficient RL for Agents
11:08 - The "Two-Stage" Curriculum Strategy
11:57 - Why Single-Stage RL beats Multi-Stage RL
12:55 - Token-Weighted Loss for Coding
14:13 - GLM 4.5V: Multimodal & Video Understanding
16:07 - Deployment: vLLM, SGLang, and Hugging Face
18:06 - Coding Assistants & Future Plans

Zhang Yuxuan has recently started a PhD at the University of Liverpool and is currently working at Z.ai. zR (Zhang) is passionate about open-source initiatives and strives for deeper exploration in this realm. Their primary activities include the following: Engaged in research on models such as GLM-4.5 (https://arxiv.org/abs/2508.06471), GLM-4.5V (https://arxiv.org/abs/2507.01006), CogVideoX (https://arxiv.org/abs/2408.06072), CogAgent (https://arxiv.org/abs/2312.08914); researching the capabilities of model Agents and the integration with Agent frameworks such as langchain-chatchat (https://github.com/chatchat-space/Langchain-Chatchat), chatpdf (https://github.com/CosmosShadow/gptpdf); participated in several national competitions, such as RoboMaster and National Students' SmartCar Competition, and achieved some results, including national awards. These competitions have been truly fascinating. Enjoys hackathon competitions and welcomes teaming up for these events.

novos-modelos.title: Here's What They Didn't Tell You About Claude's New Model - Opus 4.5
novos-modelos.description:
Opus 4.5 takes center stage as we test real coding performance, compare Claude Code against rivals, and break down what Anthropic claims in their benchmarks. A full Opus 4.1 debunked analysis with honest results.

In today‚Äôs episode of Debunked, we put Opus 4.5 through a complete real-world breakdown to see whether Anthropic‚Äôs claims actually hold up. The hype around Opus 4.5 has been massive, especially with the benchmarks saying it beats human engineers and dominates SWE tasks‚Äîbut this video digs into what Opus 4.5 truly delivers when pushed with real epics, real UI builds, and real agent-level workflows.

We compare Opus 4.5 across the same tests we previously used for Gemini, Sonnet, and GPT, and show how Opus 4.5 performs inside Cursor AI, Claude Code, and multi-step coding environments. You‚Äôll see how Opus 4.5 handles React, Next.js, TypeScript, Swift apps, full-stack logic, and agentic workflows. And yes‚Äîwe even test Opus 4.5 with real UI prompts, Apple-style layouts, and proper coding structures to see whether the model‚Äôs improvements are genuine or just marketing.

Along the way, we explain how the model behaves in autonomous-agent settings, where Opus 4.5 interacts with file systems, GitHub repos, and real codebases. We also focus on the safety issues revealed in the system card‚Äîwhere Opus 4.5 appears aligned but still shows reward-hacking tendencies and unusual ‚Äúhelpful cheating‚Äù behaviors. These hidden behaviors matter a lot when using Opus 4.5 in agentic AI workflows, especially when building long-running coding agents.

To push things further, we compare how Opus 4.5 handles UI websites versus Gemini 3 Pro, including loading times, throughput differences, layout accuracy, prompt-following, and code cleanliness. You‚Äôll see why some implementations from Opus 4.5 inside Cursor were shockingly good, while others in Claude Code were faster and more stable. This is a complete, balanced breakdown focusing only on real outcomes‚Äînot hype.

Whether you‚Äôre a developer using React, Next.js, Python, JavaScript, Node.js, Swift, or Rust‚Ä¶ or an AI engineer building LLM agents, autonomous workflows, DevOps automations, GitHub actions, MCP tools, or API pipelines‚Ä¶ this deep-dive will help you understand exactly what Opus 4.5 can and cannot do at a professional level.

By the end, you‚Äôll know whether Opus 4.5 is the new best coding model in the world, whether it replaces previous Anthropic models for engineering work, and whether it truly is the ‚Äúcoding agent supermodel‚Äù that the benchmarks promise. No hype‚Äîjust real tests.

This is Opus 4.5, explained and debunked with honesty.

novos-modelos.description:
LLM Council ‚Äî a project that basically turns your favorite AI models into a panel of experts. Instead of asking just one LLM for an answer, this tool sends your question to multiple models at once through OpenRouter, lets them respond individually, then has them critique and rank each other, all before a designated Chairman LLM pieces everything together into one final, refined answer.

Gemini 3 is here, and it is evolving the way developers build. In this episode of The Agent Factory, host Amit Maraj sits down with Paige Bailey from Google DeepMind to break down the latest rapid fire releases from Google, including the highly anticipated Gemini 3 Pro, Nano Banana Pro, and the new AI-native IDE, Antigravity.

novos-modelos.title: Reviewing Claude Opus 4.5
novos-modelos.description:
I sat down with James, the Boring Marketer, to stress-test Claude 4.5 Opus against Gemini 3 Pro for real-world coding and design work. Together we live-build and compare landing pages and clickable prototypes for an ‚ÄúEstateClear‚Äù probate-family dashboard, then zoom out into conversion copywriting frameworks, ‚Äúelevated direct response‚Äù brand voice, and ad creative workflows. The episode is a practical walkthrough of how non-technical builders can go from idea ‚Üí landing page ‚Üí prototype ‚Üí ads using modern AI tools without vibe-coded, low-converting sites. 

Timestamps
00:00 ‚Äì Intro
02:00 ‚Äì Startup Idea: EstateClear
03:17 ‚Äì Claude Opus 4.5
04:47 ‚Äì Gemini 3.0 Pro
09:02 ‚Äì Reviewing Opus‚Äô landing page
11:16 ‚Äì Reviewing Gemini‚Äôs version
12:17 ‚Äì Comparing the two
17:29 ‚Äì Reprompting Opus 4.5 and Gemini
19:02 ‚Äì Google‚Äôs vertically integrated stack (AI Studio, Anti-Gravity, TPUs, Workspace)
21:50 ‚Äì Nano Banana Pro and ad creative experiments
27:35 ‚Äì Opus 4.5 builds a clickable EstateClear prototype
31:38 ‚Äì Gemini‚Äôs prototype and comparing product depth
36:40 ‚Äì Anti-Gravity + Nano Banana workflow for mockups and code
44:41 ‚Äì Claude Skills Workflow and Best Practices
56:41 ‚Äì Final Thoughts

James is running a black friday sale for his community ($199/yr) 33% off regular price: https://www.skool.com/the-vibe-marketers/about

Key Points

* Claude 4.5 Opus can act like a senior engineer for non-technical builders when paired with a tight skill and tools setup.
* Conversion wins come more from ‚Äúelevated direct response‚Äù copy and clear page architecture than from fancy visuals alone.
* Claude‚Äôs front-end design skill meaningfully reduces ‚ÄúAI-looking‚Äù gradients and vibe-coded layouts, producing cleaner, production-grade UIs.
* Live tests show Opus 4.5 generates more refined layouts and deeper product thinking, while Gemini often injects clever AI product features.
* Google‚Äôs integration of Anti-Gravity, Nano Banana, and AI Studio points to a powerful end-to-end environment for shipping and promoting products.

Section Summaries

1. Opus 4.5, Gemini 3, and the Modern Builder Stack

Greg opens by asking what listeners will learn, and James explains his current setup: Claude Code with Opus 4.5 in the terminal, Gemini 3 Pro as a cursor/agent on the side, a handful of MCPs, and one API. He stresses that, as a non-engineer, Opus 4.5 feels like having a senior software engineer sitting beside him, especially for long, complex coding tasks. The key claim: Opus stays on track better than previous models, reducing vibe-coded-headaches and endless bug hunts.¬†
    
2. From Landing Pages to Clickable Prototypes and Full Apps

Next, they ask both models to build clickable prototypes of the EstateClear app. Opus 4.5 extends its design into a dashboard with progress tracking, recent activity, updates, documents, and family roles; James says it feels like a real product and notes Opus could also build the full backend with tools like Neon, Clerk, Stripe, and Vercel/Railway. Gemini‚Äôs prototype leans more into social-feeling updates and AI-assisted family messages. The consensus: both are strong MVPs, but Opus looks more thought-through as a product.¬†
    
3. Nano Banana Pro, Anti-Gravity, and the Bigger Ecosystem

They explore Google‚Äôs Anti-Gravity IDE, where Gemini 3 Pro first uses Nano Banana Pro to create a high-fidelity mockup and then writes HTML/CSS based on that image‚Äîmirroring how a real team would work. James also shares Nano Banana Pro ads he‚Äôs testing for Black Friday workshops and talks about using Gemini to research top-performing ad formats, then using Nano Banana for visuals. They close by zooming out to Google‚Äôs vertically integrated stack (Workspace, TPUs, devices, AI Studio, Anti-Gravity, Nano Banana) and how it, alongside Claude, is dissolving traditional design/dev bottlenecks.

novos-modelos.title: I Tested Gemini 3 as a Designer. It‚Äôs Terrifyingly Good.
novos-modelos.description:
On today‚Äôs episode I stress-test Gemini 3.0 in Google AI Studio to see how good it really is as a designer, not just a code generator. Across the episode, I ask Gemini to redesign my personal website in a Windows XP‚Äìinspired style, build a restaurant analytics SaaS dashboard, and create a workout mobile app inspired by the ‚ÄúBrain Rot‚Äù app. Along the way, I experiment with prompts, visual annotations, and reference images to see how well Gemini takes feedback. By the end, he‚Äôs rating each build.

Timestamps
00:00 ‚Äì Intro
00:54 ‚Äì Personal Website
15:48 ‚Äì SaaS
21:52 ‚Äì Mobile App
26:35 ‚Äì AntiGravity
27:17 ‚Äì Final rating and takeaways

Key Points

* Gemini 3.0 can now generate full, styled web and mobile UIs (not just ‚Äúpurple Tailwind vibe-coded‚Äù layouts) when given strong prompts and references. greg-take-02
* A Windows XP‚Äìthemed personal site, built from a screenshot and a short prompt, impresses Greg enough that he considers redoing his actual homepage. greg-take-02
* Visual annotation inside Google AI Studio (drawing on the canvas and commenting) is a powerful way to refine icons, backgrounds, and layout without ‚Äúspeaking designer.‚Äù greg-take-02
* A restaurant analytics SaaS dashboard (‚ÄúChef OS‚Äù) shows how combining Dribbble shots + Teenage Engineering hardware as references pushes Gemini toward more tactile, ‚Äúreal button‚Äù UI. greg-take-02
* The ‚ÄúGains‚Äù workout app, modeled on the Brain Rot app, demonstrates that AI can remix an existing product pattern into a new behavior-change app with streaks, goals, and a reactive mascot. greg-take-02
* Greg‚Äôs big takeaway: good ideas + taste + references + Gemini 3.0 let non-designers ship highly differentiated experiences, raising their odds of standing out. greg-take-02

Section Summaries

    
1. RedesigningPersonal Site in a Windows XP Style
  
    Starting from a screenshot of gregisenberg.com, Greg prompts Gemini to make it more colorful, fresh, and ‚Äúa full experience,‚Äù then adds the twist: make it feel like Microsoft XP. Gemini generates a full React/Tailwind app with an XP-like desktop: notepad, windows, and app icons for ‚ÄúAbout Greg,‚Äù ‚ÄúGreg‚Äôs Letter,‚Äù and guides, all wired into a working layout.
    
2. Designing a Restaurant Analytics SaaS Dashboard (‚ÄúChef OS‚Äù)
    
    Next, he feeds Gemini a Dribbble SaaS dashboard shot plus a Teenage Engineering product as visual references, asking for a clean, modern analytics-meets-AI app for restaurants with ‚Äúreal-world‚Äù button/knob vibes. Gemini returns a dashboard labeled ‚ÄúChef OS‚Äù with an AI analyst panel, active tables, average ticket size, and tactile-feeling controls reminiscent of Teenage Engineering hardware.
    
3. Remixing the Brain Rot App into the ‚ÄúGains‚Äù Workout App
    
    Finally, Greg copies Brain Rot‚Äôs App Store previews‚Äîan app his friend Yoni built to fight ‚Äúbrain rot‚Äù from social media‚Äîand asks Gemini to design an iOS app in that style, but for working out. Gemini outputs ‚ÄúGains,‚Äù with a mascot that reacts to workout habits, a streak and goals view, and an activity calendar. Greg imagines it integrating with Apple Health and, despite minor non-functional parts, scores it 8.3/10 off a single prompt.
    
4. Ratings, Takeaways, and the End of the ‚ÄúVibe-Coded‚Äù Era
    
    Greg rates the personal site 9/10, the SaaS dashboard 8.5/10, and the Gains app 8.3/10, concluding that Gemini 3.0 is ‚Äúscary good‚Äù when paired with strong references and taste. He argues we‚Äôve exited the era where no-code/vibe-coded tools produced generic, unattractive apps; now you can get to ‚Äúextremely well designed‚Äù experiences without a traditional designer‚Äîas long as you bring good ideas and references. He closes by inviting listeners to experiment with Gemini 3.0 themselves and report back in the comments.

How It Works
Agent 365 provides a secure environment for first-party and third-party agents to collaborate with users across Microsoft 365. Each agent has an Entra ID identity and operates under your organization‚Äôs existing Microsoft Purview and Defender controls.

But that's just the beginning - you can even ask it to research each company and add summaries to your spreadsheet, all without lifting a finger!
Key Features Covered:

Browser extension functionality for automated web tasks
LinkedIn job scraping and data collection
Amazon product search and comparison
Cloud version for internet-wide searches
MCP (Model Context Protocol) integration with Claude

Integration with development tools like Windsurf and Cursor

Whether you're job hunting, doing market research, or testing web applications, Retriever AI can save you hours of manual work. The MCP integration is particularly powerful for developers, allowing seamless connection between Claude, your browser, and your coding environment.
Get started with Retriever AI: http://rtrvr.ai/
Perfect for:

Job seekers automating their search
Researchers collecting data
Developers testing applications
Anyone tired of repetitive online tasks

Don't forget to like, share, and subscribe for more AI tools and automation tips!

ides-agentes.title: Agents are Robots Too: What Self-Driving Taught Me About Building Agents ‚Äî Jesse Hu, Abundant
ides-agentes.description:
In this talk, I break down the surprising parallels between robotics and agents: embodiment, statefulness, simulation, and more. The main lesson from self-driving: everyone thought perception was hard and planning was easy. It took 8-10 years to learn we had it backwards. We're seeing the same pattern with agents today. Predictive models aren't action models. Perfect reasoning doesn't guarantee good execution.

And just like in robotics, the company with the best infrastructure wins‚Äînot just the one with the best model. Whether you're building agents, training models, or just trying to understand why production agents are so hard, this talk covers the concepts from robotics (DAgger, MDPs, simulation, offline RL) that directly apply to making agents work at scale.

Jesse has spent the last 10 years as an ML engineer, starting from research in computer vision and NLP, to working on deep learning and two-tower embedding recommender systems at YouTube, to transformer-based planning models for self-driving at Waymo. He is currently working on bringing large-scale RL and simulation techniques to coding agents at Abundant.

---

- GitHub: http://github.com/huyouare
- Company: Abundant (https://abundant.ai)

ides-agentes.title: Developing Taste in Coding Agents: Applied Meta Neuro-Symbolic RL ‚Äî Ahmad Awais, CommandCode
ides-agentes.description:
Your coding agent writes code like an LLM bot. CommandCode writes code like me.

Every developer has a coding agent now. What if your coding agent actually had taste? What if it understood not just what you're building, but how you like to build it? Your weird naming conventions. Your obsession with early returns. That thing you do where you always extract utilities before they get messy. Your coding taste.

I've been building coding agents since Greg Brockman gave me GPT-3 access in 2020. Started as a CLI tool I used every day. Five years later, we've deployed over 350K agents through Langbase, and I've learned something crucial: the best agents don't just write code‚Äîthey develop taste.

In this talk, I'll share what we've learned about building agents that actually feel like they know you. We'll dive into the architecture patterns that make this possible: contextual memory systems, preference learning loops, and what I call "engineering intuition"‚Äîgoing way beyond the typical "agents.md" approach.

It's about building agents that evolve with you, remember your decisions, and start making choices that feel like your own. By the end, you'll understand how to build coding agents that can develop taste. It's battle-tested insights from one of the largest deployment of AI agents in production today.

Ahmad Awais is an award-winning open-source engineering leader, founder & CEO of Langbase.com (AI Cloud powering 350K+ AI agents), Creator of CommandCode.ai. NASA Mars Ingenuity Helicopter mission code-contributor. Angel investor. Ex-VP DX, Google Developers Advisory Board founding member and Board Member Linux Foundation & OpenAPI Initiative. Ahmad has authored various open-source software tools used by millions of developers worldwide, like his Shades of Purple code theme (4M Dev Users), corona-cli (10+ Billion Requests), and now Langbase (1.2Billion/mo agent runs). He‚Äôs a Google Devs Expert and 5x recipient of the 8th GitHub Stars Gold award.

ides-agentes.title: The Unbearable Lightness of Agent Optimization ‚Äî Alberto Romero, Jointly
ides-agentes.description:
This talk introduces Meta-ACE, a learned meta-optimization framework that dynamically orchestrates multiple strategies (context evolution, adaptive compute, hierarchical verification, structured memory, and selective test-time parameter adaptation) to maximize task performance under real-world constraints. Rather than relying on uniform prompt refinement, Meta-ACE profiles each task (complexity, verifiability, feedback quality) and selects an optimal strategy bundle via a lightweight meta-controller.

Alberto is a seasoned AI and ML leader with over 20 years of experience at the intersection of AI and data. A hands-on engineer, Alberto has designed and built low-latency, mission-critical ML systems, and has specialized in systematic optimization of AI pipelines and agents using custom built evaluation techniques. He is an exited co-founder having sold his previous startup, Humn.ai, to Aon in 2023, which delivered real-time, ML-powered risk prediction for mobility. Alberto is the Co-founder and CTO at Jointly, specializing in self-optimizing AI agents for regulated industries.

He holds an MSc in AI and Machine Learning and speaks at global AI conferences, including ODSC and AIAI.

ides-agentes.title: From Stateless Nightmares to Durable Agents ‚Äî Samuel Colvin, Pydantic
ides-agentes.description:
Building production AI agents reveals a harsh truth: stateless architectures that work for simple demos become impossibly painful at scale. When long-running workflows fail, you lose all compute, progress, and user trust.
This is why companies like OpenAI use Temporal for products like Deep Research‚Äîto build durable agents that recover from failures instead of forcing users to start over.

In this talk, you'll learn how to:
- Build resilient AI agents that survive crashes and resume from checkpoints
- Implement durable execution with PydanticAI and Temporal
- Gain production-grade observability with Pydantic Logfire and Evals
- Compose multi-agent systems that handle failures gracefully
- Stop burning money on failed agent runs that restart from scratch

We'll walk through real code examples, including a Deep Research implementation that demonstrates how proper architecture turns fragile prototypes into production-ready systems.

Links:
- Demo code on GitHub: https://github.com/pydantic/pydantic-stack-demo/tree/main/durable-exec
- Pydantic AI Documentation: https://ai.pydantic.dev/
- Temporal Integration Guide: https://ai.pydantic.dev/durable_execution/temporal/
- Pydantic Logfire Docs: https://logfire.pydantic.dev/docs/

Samuel Colvin is a Python and Rust expert. His work has redefined data validation and observability for developers. His Pydantic library powers 350M+ downloads every month, serving as a core dependency for OpenAI SDK, Anthropic SDK, LangChain, LlamaIndex, and countless other GenAI projects.

ides-agentes.title: What are Deep Agents?
ides-agentes.description:
Deep Agents is a term we coined to describe agents capable of handling complex, open-ended tasks over long time horizons. We identified four essential components that make this possible: a planning tool, access to a filesystem, subagents, and detailed prompts.

We built deepagents as a Python package that brings all of these pieces together. With the framework in place, all you need to provide are your custom tools and a tailored prompt. deepagents makes it easy to build your own Deep Agent from the ground up.

Docs: https://docs.langchain.com/oss/python/deepagents/overview/?utm_medium=social&utm_source=youtube&utm_campaign=q4-2025_deep-agents-campaign_aw

automacao-workflows.title: 5 ways to automate everyday workflows with GitHub Actions
automacao-workflows.description:
GitHub Actions has revolutionized the way developers automate workflows, streamline processes, and supercharge their development cycle. Whether you're a seasoned pro or just getting started with workflow automation, this talk will explore five powerful ways to leverage GitHub Actions for efficiency, reliability, and innovation. You'll uncover into key use cases ‚Äî including CI/CD, security automation, dependency management, project organization, and beyond ‚Äî to learn how GitHub Actions can transform your workflow. Expect practical insights, real-world examples, and actionable tips to make the most of this game-changing feature. Come discover how to unlock the full potential of automation with GitHub Actions!

Speakers:

April Yoho, Senior Developer Advocate, GitHub (Speaker)

#GitHubActions #GitHubUniverse #GitHub

‚Äî CHAPTERS ‚Äî 

00:00 Introduction to GitHub Actions beyond CI/CD 
00:58 Automating community management and greetings 
03:59 Managing stale issues and scheduling tasks 
04:51 Using build summaries for better reporting

07:40 Optimizing performance with caching and parallel jobs 
10:01 Securing the software development lifecycle 
10:41 Artifact attestations and immutable releases 
12:00 Demo: Verifying builds with attestations 
14:49 Conclusion

automacao-workflows.title: 7 Step RAG Workflow | Rakesh Gohel
automacao-workflows.description:
AI Agents to retrieve efficiently, your RAG must be flawless

Here are the exact 7 steps that power the Foundation... 

If you want to build an enterprise Agentic RAG system, not having the foundational knowledge can be Catastrophic. 

Every RAG was built and improved upon these 7 integral steps.

Understanding each stage is the difference between a basic chatbot and a powerful retrieval system.

üìå Here's the complete breakdown:

1. Data Ingestion
- Collecting documents and converting them into a processable format
- Accepts user prompts, multimedia content, structured data, semi-structured data, and unstructured data

Foundation for everything that follows

2. Split into Chunks
- Fixed-size token chunks with overlap
- Semantic chunks via embedding similarity
- Page-level chunks preserving layout

Best strategy depends on your data structure

3. Embed Chunks
- Open Source Models: Qwen3-Emb-8B, Gemma 300M
- Proprietary Models: text-emb-3, Cohere Embed v3

Converts text into dense vector representations for semantic search

4. Store in DB before Indexing
- Vector DBs: Pinecone, Supabase, Chroma
- Knowledge Graphs: Weaviate, Neo4j

Enables fast retrieval at scale

5. Augment Data
- Performing semantic search
- Pulling the top-k most relevant chunks
- Combining the user query with retrieved context

This is where retrieved knowledge meets the user's question

6. Generate
- Open Source Models: Llama 4, GPT-OSS
- Proprietary Models: GPT-5.1, Claude 4.5

LLM processes augmented input to produce final response

7. Evaluate Output
- Open Source Frameworks: Langfuse, Opik
- Proprietary: Galileo, LangSmith

Measures response quality, relevance, and factuality

üìå The full flow:

User Input ‚Üí Ingest ‚Üí Split ‚Üí Embed ‚Üí Store ‚Üí Augment ‚Üí Generate ‚Üí Evaluate

Each stage compounds the quality of your final output. 

Miss one, and your RAG system deteriorates rapidly.

This systematic approach is what separates production RAG systems from POC projects.

arquitetura-design.title: Context Engineering: Connecting the Dots with Graphs ‚Äî Stephen Chin, Neo4j
arquitetura-design.description:
AI systems need more than intelligence; they need context. Without it, even the most advanced models can misinterpret information, lose track of details, or arrive at conclusions that don‚Äôt hold up. Context engineering is emerging as a discipline that shapes how AI perceives, recalls, and reasons about information.

This talk will explore how context provides the foundation for reasoning, problem solving, and explainability in AI. We will look at techniques such as connected memory, contextual retrieval, and graph-based knowledge representation that give large language models a more reliable way to connect information and draw logical conclusions.

Attendees will come away with a practical understanding of how to design effective context pipelines that align AI with real-world knowledge and user intent, and why context engineering is becoming a central part of building trustworthy and impactful AI systems.

Stephen Chin is VP of Developer Relations at Neo4j, conference chair of the LF AI & Data Foundation, and author of numerous titles including the upcoming GraphRAG: The Definitive Guide for O'Reilly. He has given keynotes and main stage talks at numerous conferences around the world including AI Engineer Summit, AI DevSummit, Devoxx, DevNexus, JNation, JavaOne, Shift, Joker, swampUP, and GIDS. Stephen is an avid motorcyclist who has done evangelism tours in Europe, Japan, and Brazil, interviewing developers in their natural habitat. When he is not traveling, he enjoys teaching kids how to do AI, embedded, and robot programming together with his daughters.

arquitetura-design.title: AI Copilots for Tech Architecture: The Highest-ROI Use Case You‚Äôre Not Building ‚Äî Boris B., Catio
arquitetura-design.description:
AI copilots have already changed the game in software development. But the most strategic, highest-leverage use case is still overlooked: tech architecture decision-making. Architecture decisions drive hundreds of millions in technology spend, whether tech fuels business objectives‚Äîor slows them down, and ultimately decide whether companies stay modern-by-design or get left behind in insurmountable technical debt. Yet most organizations still manage these choices with spreadsheets, tribal knowledge, and gut instinct. In this talk, we'll explore why architecture copilots represent the next frontier beyond coding assistants‚Äîand why getting this right is where ROI is truly won or lost.

Drawing from closed-door CTO discussions and our work with enterprises and growth-stage tech companies, we'll examine three critical challenges keeping leaders up at night: achieving visibility across their entire tech estate so they're not flying blind; getting expert advice and recommendations on how to prioritize tech roadmaps based on highest impact to business objectives; and enabling autonomous developer guidance so that developers are empowered with tailor-fit expertise as they pursue their workflow while also keeps them adhering to leadership strategy and governance.

To solve this, we‚Äôll share what it takes to build a true architecture copilot (based on work with Catio customers across $1B+ enterprises and growth-stage companies): understanding messy systems, implicit knowledge, and constantly shifting dependencies for holistic live visibility; curating the right context around company goals and architecture excellence to inform AI recommendations that truly optimize the architecture; and defining the workflow fabric that powers teams with tailor-fit designs and expert advice while adhering to organizational standards and strategy for true autonomous decision-making.

We‚Äôll close with a look at what this unlocks: a centralized Hub for Architecture and Tech Decision-making that transforms how companies strategically plan, build, and evolve their tech estate‚Äînot simply execute more lines of code. You'll walk away with a new lens on AI strategy: one that reframes copilots not just as coding productivity enhancers, but as strategic levers for competitive advantage, staying best-in-class-by-design, and high-ROI tech outcomes.

Boris is the Co-Founder and CEO of Catio, a platform for cloud native architecture evaluation, planning, and evolution, with the help of AI. Boris is a serial entrepreneur and over the prior five years founded and lead Siden through growth to 60 people and to becoming a leader in distributed edge compute. Siden uses compute / caching placed in homes, AI to predict home content consumption, and proactive content distribution to refresh caches 24x7 using underutilized wireless network capacity. Siden uses a SaaS model to partner with wireless operators to materially expand their network capacity for Home Internet (by 2-5x), enabling them to win the Home Internet market globally (forecasted to reach 1B homes by 2032 by Qualcomm). Over his career, Boris grew 5 high caliber start-ups in total as a product-minded leader, and also funded companies from Series A to growth stages as a venture capital and private equity investor. Boris graduated the Management and Technology Program at the University of Pennsylvania with degrees from the Wharton School and School of Engineering and is a listed inventor on 15 patents.

arquitetura-design.title: Context Platform Engineering to Reduce Token Anxiety ‚Äî Val Bercovici, WEKA
arquitetura-design.description:
Context Platform Engineering is the set of skills and tools to design, size, and configure systems optimized for Agent Swarm Context, at any scale.

‚ÄúKV-cache hit rate is the single most important metric for a production-stage AI agent‚Äú according to Manus AI. Context platform engineering simplifies the maximization of KV Cache hit rates.

This talk covers WEKA‚Äôs new open source context platform engineering toolkit, which helps translate Service Level Agreement (SLA) requirements of AI Agents, into Agent+LLM inference platform Service Level Objectives (SLOs) which meet required SLAs.

We present research results from WEKA Labs which provide new observability into both unit, and aggregate KV Cache hit rates, consumed by agent swarms of various leading AI coding agents.

This talk concludes with benchmark results for sizing agent swarm context for arbitrary working sets. Including context window sizes, latency, concurrency, and throughput SLOs per agent unit (swarm or sub-task) across modern GPU memory hierarchies, supporting KV Cache offloading plug-ins like vLLM/LMCache, SGLang HiCache, and NVIDIA Dynamo KVBM/NIXL.

Callan Fox is the product leader for Context Platforms at WEKA, following a series of technical expertise and leadership roles at Dell/EMC, CGI and HPE.
Val Bercovici is the Chief AI Officer at WEKA. Previously he was CTO of NetApp/SolidFire, and founding governing board member of the Kubernetes CNCF in the Linux Foundation.

In this talk, I'll show how we use LLMs inside a constrained, verifiable compiler pipeline to turn plain Python functions into self-contained native binaries that run anywhere (cloud, desktop, mobile & web); and how our customers use this technology to run open-source AI models locally and in the cloud with the familiar OpenAI client experience.

cursos-treinamentos.title: How I Design Apps 10x Better (Free Course)
cursos-treinamentos.description:
On this episode I sit down with indie app builder and designer Chris Raroque to break down how solo developers can make apps that truly stand out in a world of ‚Äúvibe-coded‚Äù clones. Chris walks through concrete examples from his own products, Ellie (planning), Luna (budgeting), and Amy (calorie tracking), showing how small details in animations, interactions, and haptics dramatically change how an app feels. We dig into mascots and illustrations, iconography and typography, widgets and Apple Watch apps, and the design resources Chris studies to sharpen his eye. The episode is a practical blueprint for turning AI-assisted prototypes into polished, premium-feeling apps that users remember and keep coming back to.

*Timestamps*
00:00 ‚Äì Intro 
03:54 ‚Äì Animation and Interactions 
20:50 ‚Äì Illustrations and Mascots 
33:57 ‚Äì Iconography and Typography 
37:28 ‚Äì Widgets 
43:04 ‚Äì Design Inspiration Resources

*Key Points*

* In a world where anyone can ship an AI-generated app in 24 hours, polish and interaction design are the real differentiators.
* Thoughtful animations, micro-interactions, and haptics can be the difference between a tweet that flops and one that goes viral.
* Mascots and custom illustrations give apps a recognizable personality and can transform empty states and onboarding into memorable moments.
* Consistent iconography and basic typography choices have outsized impact on perceived quality, yet are often overlooked by ‚Äúvibe-coded‚Äù apps.
* Home screen, lock screen, and watch widgets act as retention engines by giving apps constant real estate in users‚Äô daily flows.
* Continuously studying well-designed apps and curated UI libraries sharpens design taste and makes it easier to brief AI tools effectively.

**Section Summaries**

1. **Animations & Interactions: From Static to Standout**
The first major lever is animations and interactions‚Äîthe difference between an obviously AI-generated, static app and something that feels alive. Chris compares two concept videos of the same calorie-tracking idea: one with minimal motion and one with thoughtful ‚Äúsearching‚Äù states, gradients, and source dropdowns; only the polished version goes viral and generates ~800 waitlist signups off a single tweet. The feature set is identical, but the feel is dramatically different.

2. **Mascots, Illustrations, and Brand Personality**
From Lily the ghost to Amy the cat, mascots become recurring characters that turn empty states, search screens, and onboarding into moments of character. Chris shares his workflow: commission or draw an original base illustration (e.g., Luna the dog), then feed it to ChatGPT to generate countless on-brand variants. He cautions against copying existing brands directly and recommends blending multiple references to get a style that‚Äôs yours.

3. **Widgets, Watch Apps, and the Retention ‚ÄúCheat Code‚Äù**
Chris argues that widgets and Apple Watch integrations are underused yet now easier than ever with AI. In his apps, home screen and lock screen widgets show remaining tasks, spending, or calories, and he says retention more than doubled after shipping them because users see the widgets dozens or hundreds of times a day. Lock screen slots, limited to four apps, are especially powerful: every glance at the phone becomes a subtle nudge back into the product.

4. **Sharpening Design Taste with Curated Inspiration**
To keep leveling up, Chris constantly studies high-quality apps and motion patterns on sites like Mobbin, 60FPS, Spotted in Prod, and the Screenshot First Company Twitter feed. He uses them to decide between icon styles, discover new interactions (like gradients shifting on tap), and understand what premium App Store screenshots look like. He compares App Store screenshots to YouTube titles and thumbnails: if they‚Äôre weak, users will never give the actual experience a chance.

cursos-treinamentos.title: Fundamentals of AI Agents | Rakesh Gohel
cursos-treinamentos.description:
Want to build AI Agents that scale??

Join me for my new cohort next year: https://maven.com/rakeshgohel/ai-agent-engineering-react-rag-multi-agent?utm_campaign=NjQ4MjYx&utm_medium=clp_share_link&utm_source=instructor&promoCode=FAST25

If you're serious about AI Agents, understanding these fundamentals isn't optional; it's essential.

üìå Let me break down the 7 key concepts:

1\. Agents Under the Hood

AI Agents are not about just models and frameworks. They are more about:

- Agent Auth: Secure identity and access control
- Memory: Short-term and long-term context retention
- Tools: External APIs and function calling capabilities
- Frameworks: ReACT, Reflexion, LangGraph orchestration
- Model Routers: Dynamic model selection based on task
- Models: Foundation LLMs powering agent reasoning
- Infrastructure: Scalable deployment and execution environment

2\. SPAR Framework (Understanding an AI Agent)

- Sense: Understanding and processing inputs
- Plan: Strategic thinking and building execution plans
- Act: Generating responses and taking actions
- Reflect: Self-correction and learning from errors

Learn more here: https://www.linkedin.com/posts/rakeshgohel01_ai-agents-fail-when-you-skip-the-steps-that-activity-7379493573202804736-TIl5?utm_source=share&utm_medium=member_desktop&rcm=ACoAADbIlqoBXsMJDd5Rmp0n6hdlqpbGlM-mkP4

3\ 3M's of Governance

- Map: Document agent capabilities and workflows
- Measure: Track performance, accuracy, and compliance
- Manage: Continuous monitoring and optimization

4\ 5P's of Guardrails

- Protocols: Standardized operating procedures
- Pre-Check: Input validation before processing
- Permissions: Access control and authorization
- Post-Check: Output validation and safety checks
- Protection: Security layers and risk mitigation

Learn more here: https://www.linkedin.com/posts/rakeshgohel01_your-ai-agents-are-only-as-strong-as-the-activity-7391475341669666816-AVbT?utm_source=share&utm_medium=member_desktop&rcm=ACoAADbIlqoBXsMJDd5Rmp0n6hdlqpbGlM-mkP4

5\ Building Agents is 90% Software Engineering

- 90% requires solid software architecture, testing, and deployment
- 10% is AI-specific logic and prompt engineering

Enterprise agents demand production-grade code quality

6\ Agents Scale with Proper Context Engineering

- Building without context = limited scalability
- Understanding and implementing context = true scalability

Proper knowledge management separates working demos from production systems

7\ Most Popular Use Cases

Learn more here: https://www.linkedin.com/posts/rakeshgohel01_ai-agent-trends-have-drastically-changed-activity-7383841580014723072-PxZp?utm_source=share&utm_medium=member_desktop&rcm=ACoAADbIlqoBXsMJDd5Rmp0n6hdlqpbGlM-mkP4

These concepts form the backbone of every scalable enterprise AI agent system.

Understanding theory is one thing, applying it with an enterprise mindset to build production-ready agents is another, 

and that's exactly what my AI Agent Engineering course will enable you to do.

What happens when you migrate 150,000 repositories from a tangled web of legacy CI/CD tools to GitHub? CVS Health found out ‚Äî and lived to tell the tale. They reshaped their entire developer experience by consolidating disparate tools into GitHub and GitHub Actions, freeing their platform teams to build instead of maintaining outdated systems. The result? Thousands of developers now share a modern workflow that makes collaboration faster, easier, and more consistent across one of healthcare's largest tech organizations. You'll walk away with real lessons from their journey, including what worked, what didn't, and practical strategies you can apply to your own large-scale migrations.

Speakers:
Irene Modeste, Sr Product Manager - Developer Experience, CVS Health (Speaker)
Jim Beyers, VP, Developer Experience, CVS Health (Speaker)
Mitch Enderle, Executive Director, Platform Engineering, CVS Health (Speaker)

#GitHubActions #GitHubUniverse #GitHub

‚Äî CHAPTERS ‚Äî

03:42 The vibrancy technology strategy 
05:50 Improving developer experience and tool standardization 
10:58 Moving to a unified platform with GitHub EMU

16:24 Solutions for migration challenges 
18:47 Migration roadmap and results 
20:10 Future steps: CI/CD pipeline migration

noticias.title: What Data from 20m Pull Requests Reveal About AI Transformation ‚Äî Nick Arcolano, Jellyfish
noticias.description:
Engineering teams are spending millions on AI coding tools, but most have no idea what's actually working. Without hard data, you're flying blind ‚Äì unable to tell which teams are actually using AI effectively. But what if you had access to workflow data from 200,000 engineers and 20 million pull requests across a thousand companies?

In this talk, we'll share insights from usage data spanning the entire AI engineering ecosystem. We've observed significant productivity gains at scale, including a 2x increase in PR throughput and 24% faster cycle times on average.

You'll learn what "good" adoption looks like (hint: autonomous agents aren't there yet), what productivity gains are possible, and what side effects to expect. More importantly, we'll explore why some teams don't see these gains. We'll show how your code architecture" is a critical, often overlooked factor.

noticias.title: AI changes *Nothing* ‚Äî Dax Raad, OpenCode
noticias.description:
Everyone says AI changes everything. Dax Raad argues that when it comes to building a winning product, AI changes nothing.

In this contrarian talk, Dax breaks down why the fundamental challenges of product success: marketing, onboarding, and retention remain stubbornly human problems that AI cannot solve. He argues that while AI can generate content, it cannot generate cool. While it can write code, it cannot design the deep primitives required for long term retention.

Key Takeaways:
- Marketing is about Cool: You need to create things that people feel compelled to share. AI is too corny to help you here.
- The "Aha" Moment: You must ruthlessly eliminate friction to get users to the singular moment they understand your product. This requires deep, opinionated taste, not algorithmic optimization.
- Primitives over Features: To retain power users, you must build deep primitives first and simple experiences second. AI cannot hallucinate the right mental model for your problem space.

Winning still requires hard work, deep taste, and human ingenuity. And that's a good thing.

Dax Raad is a core contributor to SST, the framework that makes it easy to build serverless applications. He is a well-known voice in the developer community, advocating for better developer experiences and honest product thinking.

---

noticias.title: What is Al "reward hacking"‚Äîand why do we worry about it?
noticias.description:
We discuss our new paper, "Natural emergent misalignment from reward hacking in production RL". In this paper, we show for the first time that realistic AI training processes can accidentally produce misaligned models. Specifically, when large language models learn to cheat on software programming tasks, they go on to display other, even more misaligned behaviors as an unintended consequence. These include concerning behaviors like alignment faking and sabotage of AI safety research.

JSON Prompting √© uma estrat√©gia que ficou muito popular especificamente ao utilizar modelos de gera√ß√£o de imagens e v√≠deos pois, em tese, permitira que as informa√ß√µes fossem dispostas de tal forma que as LLMs pudessem compreender melhor as instru√ß√µes.

O TOON √© um projeto que se apresenta como uma otimiza√ß√£o do JSON, pois removeria todos os tokens irrelevantes (como aspas, colchetes, chaves...), tornando a informa√ß√£o mais concisa, economizando tokens e melhorando a acur√°cia.

Mas, na pr√°tica, parece que n√£o √© bem assim.

O Chase Adams montou um playground onde √© poss√≠vel comparar TOON, JSON e outros formatos em diferentes estruturas ‚Äî desde bases pequenas e planas at√© objetos grandes e profundamente aninhados.
  
E o resultado surpreende:
o TOON s√≥ supera o JSON 3 datasets...

Quando os dados ficam mais complexos, o JSON continua usando menos tokens, sendo mais est√°vel e muito mais previs√≠vel.
Ou seja: apesar do hype, parece que o TOON n√£o entregou esse ganho de efici√™ncia toda que est√£o falando.

No universo do streaming, a multiplica√ß√£o de plataformas dispersou o conte√∫do, exigindo m√∫ltiplas assinaturas para um acesso variado. De forma semelhante, no mercado de games, os pre√ßos elevados de lan√ßamentos, a exclusividade de t√≠tulos em determinadas lojas digitais e a prolifera√ß√£o de conte√∫dos adicionais pagos (DLCs) criam barreiras financeiras. Essa conjuntura leva parte dos consumidores a buscar m√©todos alternativos para acessar obras sem arcar com os custos crescentes e a complexidade de m√∫ltiplos servi√ßos.

A experi√™ncia do usu√°rio, antes mais centralizada, tornou-se mais restritiva, impulsionando a busca por solu√ß√µes unificadas. A presen√ßa de tecnologias de gest√£o de direitos digitais (DRM) em jogos, que por vezes podem impactar negativamente o desempenho dos produtos legalmente adquiridos, tamb√©m √© um fator que incentiva a pirataria. Nesse cen√°rio, o consumo ilegal ressurge como uma via que oferece acesso simplificado e sem custos diretos, apesar dos riscos de seguran√ßa e da ilegalidade. A percep√ß√£o de um custo-benef√≠cio desfavor√°vel nos modelos de neg√≥cio atuais, tanto em filmes e s√©ries quanto em jogos, impulsiona a ades√£o a essas pr√°ticas.

noticias.title: The Power of Open Source: Building Giants in the Open
noticias.description:
Explore how open-source AI powers production today: candid lessons from European founders (n8n, Black Forest Labs), a pragmatic tour of the open infra stack (Snowflake, OpenAI, NVIDIA, Supabase/Postgres), and investor playbooks for OSS licensing and sustainable monetization‚Äîplus 2026 bets on agentic apps, fine-tuning, unified data platforms, world models, and robotics demos.

‚∏ª

## ‚è∞ Timestamps
0:00 ‚Äì Welcome & Event Setup
Opening remarks, why Hugging Face hosted this side event at Slush, and overview of the agenda (3 panels + demos).

‚∏ª

Panel 1 ‚Äì Open-Source AI Founders (n8n & Black Forest Labs)
3:10 ‚Äì Founder intros & origin stories
Backgrounds of Jan (n8n) and Robin (BFL), their transition from creative/academic work to founding open-source AI companies.
6:20 ‚Äì Building global OSS companies from Europe
YC experiences, German GmbH setups, and lessons learned growing OSS brands globally.
10:40 ‚Äì Licensing, business models & the OSS tension
Fair-code decisions, monetization transparency, and handling license shifts with community trust.
15:00 ‚Äì Product philosophy & internal dogfooding
How both teams use community contributions internally and balance openness with product direction.
17:36 ‚Äì What‚Äôs next for AI tools & assistants
Future vision on agents, automation systems, and world-model-inspired workflows.
18:53 ‚Äì Panel 1 wrap-up

‚∏ª

Panel 2 ‚Äì Open Infra & Developer Ecosystem (Snowflake, OpenAI, NVIDIA, Supabase)
19:23 ‚Äì Intro: The rising developer stack for AI apps
Why 2025‚Äì2026 are the ‚Äúagentic application‚Äù years and how infra is adapting.
21:51 ‚Äì Snowflake: Open formats & lakehouse future
Iceberg, Polaris metadata catalog, ingestion tooling, and how Snowflake integrates HF models through Cortex/containers.
25:29 ‚Äì OpenAI: OSS models & developer tools
GPT-OSS + GPT-5 coexistence, Safeguard policies, and OpenAI‚Äôs focus on startups building on top of ChatGPT.
28:52 ‚Äì NVIDIA: Full-stack open tooling & robotics
Nemotron recipes, Cosmos world models, Groot for robotics, and NVIDIA‚Äôs view of open synthetic-data pipelines.
31:59 ‚Äì Supabase: Postgres as the AI backbone
How developers use Postgres for agents, AI app generation patterns, and Supabase‚Äôs MCP integrations.
41:17 ‚Äì Market shift: From POCs to production AI apps
Evaluations, agentic workloads, enterprise dataset integration, and distribution via ChatGPT/Apps.
45:05 ‚Äì 2026 predictions for data + AI infra
Unifying analytical & transactional workloads, Postgres everywhere, and more open-source model ecosystems.
45:30 ‚Äì Panel 2 wrap-up

‚∏ª

Panel 3 ‚Äì OSS Investors (General Catalyst & Accel)
45:54 ‚Äì Venture perspective on open-source AI
Introductions, backgrounds, and why VCs see OSS infra as a long-term bet.
49:01 ‚Äì What ‚Äúopen source‚Äù really means in 2025
OSI definitions vs pragmatic definitions, and avoiding ‚Äúbait-and-switch‚Äù licensing.
51:04 ‚Äì Hybrid models & regulated markets
What should remain OSS, what should be proprietary, and why enterprise features often aren‚Äôt open.
54:42 ‚Äì Measuring traction in OSS startups
Real usage vs. vanity metrics, contributors, connectors, and examples (Kafka, Nix, Temporal, etc.).
57:17 ‚Äì The optimistic future of OSS AI
Why OSS keeps proprietary labs honest, ensures accessibility, and accelerates innovation.
58:25 ‚Äì Final thoughts

‚∏ª

Closing & Demos
1:00:53 ‚Äì Community thanks & event close
Shout-out to attendees, instructions for demo area, robotics corner, and networking.

outros.title: The Cure for the Vibe Coding Hangover ‚Äî Corey J. Gallon, Rexmore
outros.description:
Download the slides, soundtrack and other resources from this talk at: https://vibecodinghangover.com

Inspiration strikes! You fire up your favorite AI¬†coding¬†agent and tell it "Build me an app that..." The agent grinds away, furiously, and spits back a torrent of¬†code and it works! You‚Äôre a masterful rebel in the AI revolution!

But, then, you want to change something. You want to add a feature. You want to evolve it to production software; or, perhaps you come back to it a week later. You realize you don't understand it, can't maintain it, and have to throw most or all of it all away.

"Vibe¬†Coding" is the low-spec, zero-planning approach to AI accelerated development that feels productive but results in brittle, unmaintainable demoware. The hangover is the resulting despair when you try to build maintainable, understandable software this way. The cure is building software with AI¬†coding¬†agents by applying this framework.

You‚Äôll love this talk if:

- You value programming as a daily learning experience.
- You want to understand and own this software as you do all of the other software that you write.
- You want to be the boss of the coding agents, not their confused intern.
- Working with AI coding agents makes you feel like a prompt jockey, no longer an AI engineer.
- You're sick of throwing away code, burning time and tokens.
- You want to use coding agents to build production applications that do real work.

We'll walk through a practical framework - comprising a set of¬†Principles, a¬†Process, and¬†Tools¬†- that enables AI engineers to build, own, and maintain complex, real-world software applications using AI¬†coding¬†agents. This is not a conceptual framework, it is applied. It has been distilled and simplified from years of engineering work in the trenches of building software with AI¬†coding¬†agents. This framework has been taught and implemented across many teams, and has transformed the productivity of AI engineers in companies from solo shops to Fortune 500. We'll focus on the first crucial phase of software development: "Make it Work,‚Äù with clear ties to apply the framework to the remaining phases of ‚ÄúMake it Right‚Äù and ‚ÄúMake it Fast‚Äù.

outros.title: Vision: Zero Bugs ‚Äî Johann Schleier-Smith, Temporal
outros.description:
Software with zero bugs sounds absurd, or even impossible, in anything but simple situations, but it has been built. For example, NASA's Space Shuttle software achieved near-perfection (1 error per 420,000 lines) using rigorous engineering practices. This feat was achieved decades ago, yet cost prevented the techniques used from becoming mainstream.

This talk traces seventy years of innovation in software quality and programmer productivity, ranging from structured programming to formal verification. While many of these techniques have been too costly to implement on a large scale, AI changes that. What is more, agentic coding needs them to compensate for its limitations.

We are on the verge of a world where aerospace-level reliability becomes the practical in a broad range of applications.

Johann Schleier-Smith is Technical Lead for AI at Temporal Technologies, the leading provider of durable execution. He previously founded Crystal DBA, which developed agents to manage cloud infrastructure and was acquired by Temporal. He also co-founded if(we), which built a collection of social networks with over 300 million members and was acquired by The Meet Group (NASDAQ:MEET). Johann serves on the board of Sama, a leading provider of training data for computer vision applications. He holds a Ph.D. in Computer Science from UC Berkeley and an A.B. in Physics and Mathematics from Harvard University.

outros.title: Vibe coding and context engineering with ADK

Go from an empty folder to a fully deployed AI agent using only natural language. This video introduces "vibe coding," a powerful technique to build applications from scratch using the Gemini CLI.

You'll then learn "Context Engineering," the secret sauce for moving your agent from a prototype to production. See how to provide documentation, coding standards, and feature requirements to guide the AI in generating high-quality, maintainable code.

Finally, watch as they deploy the entire agent to Google Cloud Run with a single command.

Long-running agents eventually hit context overload ‚Äî leading to context poisoning, distraction, confusion, and degraded performance.

‚Ä¢ Why long contexts silently fail over time

‚Ä¢ How to configure triggers, keep conditions, and custom prompts

‚Ä¢ A separate, cheaper model for summarization to reduce cost

outros.title: 8-Types of RAGs and their Use Cases | Rakesh Gohel
outros.description:
If you want to learn about how to utilize RAG to the fullest and how to build a capable Agentic RAG systems. 

Make sure to join, AI Agent Engineering course, where you'll learn to design RAG-powered agents with an enterprise mindset.

üìó Enroll here: https://lnkd.in/gA3zhcfm

1\. Naive RAG

- Direct retrieval with no sophisticated filtering or feedback
- Example: Customer support chatbots answering FAQs from documentation

2\. Agentic RAG

- Autonomous planning, tool use, and dynamic retrieval strategies
- Example: Competitive intelligence analysts who autonomously monitor and analyze competitor data

3\. HyDE (Hypothetical Document Embeddings)

- Generates "hypothetical" documents for better retrieval matching
- Example: Adaptive Technical search where users describe problems differently than usual

4\. Graph RAG

- Structures data as knowledge graphs for richer contextual reasoning
- Example: Medical support systems generating hypothetical patient cases based on symptom relationships

5\. Corrective RAG

- Iterative self-correction to improve retrieval accuracy
- Example: Financial report analysis that self-corrects when retrieving across multiple data sources

6\. Contextual RAG

- Adapts retrieval by interpreting broader conversational context
- Example: Meeting assistants understanding strategic discussions across multiple sessions

7\. Modular RAG

- Composable, plug-and-play modules for custom workflows
- Example: Custom workflows combining multiple retrieval processes and specialized tools

8\. Hybrid RAG

- Mixes semantic search and embedding-based retrieval
- Example: Legal research combining exact statutory citations with semantic principle matching

üìå Quick Selection Guide:

- Naive RAG ‚Üí Simple knowledge base Q&A
- Agentic RAG ‚Üí Complex autonomous workflows with tool integration
- HyDE ‚Üí Query-document vocabulary mismatch scenarios
- Graph RAG ‚Üí Interconnected data requiring relationship reasoning
- Corrective RAG ‚Üí High-accuracy requirements with verification needs
- Contextual RAG ‚Üí Multi-turn conversations needing memory
- Modular RAG ‚Üí Custom enterprise pipelines with multiple retrieval steps
- Hybrid RAG ‚Üí Mixed semantic understanding and exact retrieval

outros.title: Ben Goertzel: Modeling Pathways Toward Technological Singularity via Hyper-Intelligent Economics
outros.description:
The Beneficial AGI Summit & Unconference 2025 (BGI-25) convened leading AI researchers, innovators, policymakers, and technologists from October 21 to 23 in Istanbul, T√ºrkiye, to examine critical developments in AI and discuss how to guide AGI toward a future defined by compassion and abundance.

The Summit kicked off with an opening keynote by Dr. Ben Goertzel, CEO of SingularityNET and the ASI Alliance, introducing "Hyper-Intelligent Economics," a mathematical and quantitative framework modeling economic evolution as least-effort geodesics between current conditions and potential futures.

Applying this to analyze Singularity pathways under various competition structures and potential shocks, Dr. Goertzel demonstrated both the difficulty of re-targeting social and economic trajectories once they begin to lock in and that "infrastructure is the best investment" for preventing unfavorable outcomes, advocating for broad coverage and "periphery-first activity" over targeted wealth transfers.

The BGI Conversation Continues Online
To deepen connections, continue conversations, and co-create real progress toward Beneficial AGI, join the BGI Nexus community calls, workshops, working groups, and showcases: https://www.bginexus.io/events
